'''Alexandre M<U+00E9>nard-Burrows''' (born April 11, 1981) is a [[Canadian]] professional [[ice hockey]] winger with the [[Vancouver Canucks]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL). He is known for playing in the style of an [[pest (hockey)|agitator]]<ref>{{Citeweb|title=Canucks winger excels at ruffling feathers|url=http://www2.canada.com/ottawacitizen/news/sports/story.html?id=a1056efb-6c3a-4c62-9f91-10606e084a76|accessdate=2009-03-31|date=2007-04-27|publisher=''[[Ottawa Citizen]]''}}</ref><ref name=feisty>{{Citeweb|url=http://www.thehockeynews.com/articles/13440-Feisty-Alex-Burrows-not-worried-about-losing-friends-around-the-NHL.html|title=Feisty Alex Burrows not worried about losing friends around the NHL|publisher=''[[The Hockey News]]''|accessdate=2009-03-31}}</ref> and for his ascension to the NHL from being an undrafted player in the [[ECHL]].<ref name=feisty/><ref>{{Citeweb|title=Burrows took long road to show|url=http://www.canada.com/victoriatimescolonist/news/sports/story.html?id=fafb22c7-4237-4479-b3d3-f5277ddd798a|accessdate=2009-03-31|publisher=''[[Victoria Times Colonist]]''}}</ref>

==Playing career==
===Minor leagues===
Burrows played two seasons of [[junior hockey#Major-Junior|major junior]] in the [[Quebec Major Junior Hockey League]] (QMJHL) with the [[Shawinigan Cataractes]].  Undrafted by an [[National Hockey League|NHL]] club, Burrows joined the [[ECHL]] with the [[Greenville Grrrowl]] in [[2002<U+2013>03 ECHL season|2002<U+2013>03]].  Late in his professional rookie season, he transferred to the [[Baton Rouge Kingfish]] and finished with a combined 32 points in 66 games between the two teams.  

The following season, in [[2003<U+2013>04 ECHL season|2003<U+2013>04]], he returned to the South Division, signed by the [[Vancouver Canucks]]' ECHL affiliate, the [[Columbia Inferno]].  He was suspended for three games and fined an undisclosed amount on November 3, 2003, for abusing officials during a game on October 24 against [[Greensboro Generals]].<ref>{{citenews|title=title=Transactions|url=http://news.google.ca/newspapers?id=a5Y1AAAAIBAJ&sjid=8igMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3791,1563698&dq=alexandre-burrows&hl=en|accessdate=2010-04-02|date=2003-11-04|publisher=''[[Observer-Reporter]]''}}</ref>  He finished the season improving to 29 goals and 73 points, second in team scoring to league scoring champion [[Tim Smith (ice hockey)|Tim Smith]].<ref>{{Citeweb|title=2003-04 Columbia Inferno [ECHL]|url=http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/leagues/seasons/teams/0026962004.html|accessdate=2009-03-31|publisher=HockeyDb.com}}</ref>  During the season, he was named to the 2004 [[ECHL All-Star Game]] for the Eastern Conference and recorded one assist.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Walby Shows Skills Among ECHL All-Stars|url=http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/?id=2995465|accessdate=2009-03-31|date=2004-01-20|publisher=OurSports Central}}</ref><ref name=moosecontract/>  Following the competition, the ''[[Peoria Journal-Star]]'', a local newspaper of the All-Star Game host city, conducted a survey of the NHL scouts in attendance and listed Burrows as one of the top four prospects at the game.<ref>{{Citeweb|title=ECHL notebook 01/25/04|url=http://chronicle.augusta.com/stories/012504/lyn_041-2061.000.shtml|accessdate=2009-03-31|date=2004-01-25|publisher=''[[Augusta Chronicle]]''}}</ref>  Early in Burrows' All-Star season with Columbia, he was also signed by their [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) affiliate, the [[Manitoba Moose]] on October 21, 2003,<ref name=moosecontract>{{citeweb|title=Moose Sign Eastman and Burrows|url=http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/?id=3069970&l_id=&t_id=|accessdate=2009-03-31|date=2003-10-21|publisher=OurSports Central}}</ref> having been scouted by general manager [[Craig Heisinger]].<ref>{{citenews|title=Bird dog bolsters Canucks|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Hockey/AHL/2005/11/11/1302515-sun.html|accessdate=2010-04-02|date=2005-11-11|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|author=Adam Wazny}}</ref>  He debuted in 2 AHL games for them before being sent back down to the ECHL.  

In the subsequent off-season, he was re-signed by the Moose on August 3, 2004.<ref name=moosecontract/>  He was initially sent back down to the ECHL after a training camp he and head coach [[Randy Carlyle]] both described as disappointing.<ref name=wintering>{{citenews|title=Wintering in Winnipeg|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Hockey/AHL/2004/11/16/717055.html|accessdate=2010-04-02|date=2004-11-16|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|author=Adam Wanzy}}</ref>  After being recalled on October 29, 2004, due to an injury to [[Wade Brookbank]],<ref name=wintering/><ref>{{Citenews|title=Big line getting attention|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Hockey/AHL/2004/11/22/725940.html|accessdate=2010-04-02|date=2004-11-22|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|author=Adam Wanzy}}</ref> he scored his first AHL goal with the Moose on November 4, 2004, a [[game winning goal]] against [[David LeNeveu]] over the [[Utah Grizzlies]] in a 2<U+2013>1 win.<ref>{{Citeweb|title=Moose put one in win column|url=http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/?id=3098663&l_id=&t_id=|accessdate=2009-03-31|date=2004-11-05|publisher=OurSports Central}}</ref>  He finished the [[2004<U+2013>05 AHL season|2004<U+2013>05 season]] with Manitoba and posted 26 points over 72 games in a fourth-line role.<ref>{{citenews|title=Fourth-liners make life miserable|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Hockey/AHL/2005/01/10/883901.html|accessdate=2010-04-02|date=2005-01-10|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|author=Adam Wanzy}}</ref>

===Vancouver Canucks===
Having worked his way up from the ECHL, Burrows' energetic play in the minors earned him a two-way contract with the Moose's NHL affiliate, the [[Vancouver Canucks]], on November 9, 2005.<ref>{{Citeweb|title=Canucks Sign Burrows, Rypien|url=http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/?id=3238919|accessdate=2009-03-31|date=2005-11-09|publisher=OurSports Central}}</ref> He had appeared earlier in the Canucks' training camp for the 2005<U+2013>06 season, but was sent back to the Moose.<ref name=staking/>  He received his first NHL call-up from the Canucks that season on January 2, 2006,<ref>{{citeweb|last=Kerr|first=Grant|title=Canucks need to go on offence to fix defense|url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/LAC.20060214.KERR14/TPStory/TPSports/|publisher=Globe and Mail|accessdate=2008-03-17}}</ref> and has since established himself on the team's roster.  Shortly after being called up, Burrows scored his first career NHL goal and assist against [[Ed Belfour]] of the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] in a 4<U+2013>3 win on January 10, 2006.<ref>{{Citeweb|title=Canucks fend off Maple Leafs|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/story/2006/01/10/leafs-canucks060110.html|accessdate=2009-03-31|date=2006-01-10|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]]}}</ref>  Later that season, he added his first NHL career [[hat trick]] on March 27, 2006, in a 7<U+2013>4 win against the [[Los Angeles Kings]].<ref>{{Citeweb|title=Tricky rookie gets a hat trick|url=http://www2.canada.com/theprovince/news/sports/story.html?id=6f388340-1128-4a4a-abfe-4ad13fd0a867|accessdate=2009-03-31|date=2006-03-28|publisher=''[[The Province]]''}}</ref>  Splitting the season between the Moose and Canucks, he finished with 7 goals and 5 assists for 12 points in his NHL rookie campaign to go with 30 points in 33 AHL games.  Burrows' ascension to the NHL has been attributed to his hard-working and abrasive style of play, generating energy and aggravating opposing players.<ref>{{citeweb|last=Macinnis|first=Matt|title=Canucks 2005-06 rookie review|url=http://www.hockeysfuture.com/articles/8679/canucks200506_rookie_review/|publisher=Hockey's Future, Inc.|accessdate=2008-03-17}}</ref>

[[Image:Alex Burrows 2009.jpg|thumb|left|Burrows in [[2008<U+2013>09 NHL season|2009]]]]
Burrows completed his first full campaign with the Canucks the following season in [[2006<U+2013>07 NHL season|2006<U+2013>07]].  He contributed primarily on the team's penalty kill,<ref>{{citeweb|title=Canucks' P.K. more than okay|url=http://www2.canada.com/vancouversun/news/sports/story.html?id=840513cb-c90c-4a1e-a898-14ad1661cd13|accessdate=2009-03-31|date=2007-01-10|publisher=''[[Vancouver Sun]]''}}</ref> which finished first overall in the league, but failed to significantly produce offensively.  In [[2007<U+2013>08 NHL season|2007<U+2013>08]], Burrows formed an effective two-way shutdown duo with center [[Ryan Kesler]], countering opposing teams' top lines while contributing offensively, as well.<ref>{{citeweb|title=It takes two|url=http://canucks.nhl.com/team/app/?service=page&page=NewsPage&articleid=355420|accessdate=2009-02-05|date=2008-03-01|publisher=[[Vancouver Canucks]]}}</ref><ref>{{Citeweb|title=Kesler, Burrows score A in chemistry|url=http://www2.canada.com/theprovince/news/sports/story.html?id=b8491154-a15f-48ff-8c2b-266fe7060216|accessdate=2009-03-31|date=2008-03-12|publisher=''[[The Province]]''}}</ref>  He completed the season with a career high 12 goals, 31 points and a team high [[plus/minus]] of +11, resulting in his first of two consecutive team [[Most Exciting Player Award]]s.  

After remaining on the third line with Kesler at the start of the following season, head coach [[Alain Vigneault]] separated the two after the [[NHL All-Star Game|All-Star]] break, placing Burrows on the first line with [[Daniel Sedin|Daniel]] and [[Henrik Sedin]], beginning on February 12, 2009, during a game against the [[Phoenix Coyotes]].<ref>{{Citeweb|title=Burrows, Kesler better off separate|url=http://www.theprovince.com/sports/Burrows+Kesler+better+separate/1309235/story.html|accessdate=2009-03-31|date=2009-02-20|publisher=''[[The Province]]''}}</ref><ref name=promotion>{{citenews|title=Burrows earns promotion|url=http://www.faceoff.com/hockey/teams/vancouver-canucks/story.html?id=1287412&add_feed_url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.faceoff.com%2Fscripts%2FSP6Atom.aspx%3Fid%3D830270|accessdate=2010-03-15|date=2009-02-13|publisher=''[[Vancouver Sun]]''|author=Brad Ziemer}}</ref>  Burrows' crash-the-net style combined well with the Sedin's cycling.<ref>{{citenews|title=Canucks' Alex Burrows is modest about his legend label|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/nhl/article/2009-04-22/canucks-alex-burrows-modest-about-his-legend-label|accessdate=2010-04-02|date=2009-04-22|publisher=''[[Sporting News]]''|author=[[Canadian Press]]}}</ref>  Vigneault's line juggling was precipitated by a losing skid in January.  The Canucks' winless streak extended to eight games and nine games at home until February 3, 2009, when Burrows broke a 3<U+2013>3 tie with a [[shorthanded goal|shorthanded]] [[breakaway (ice hockey)|breakaway]] goal with 82 seconds remaining in regulation.<ref>{{Citeweb|title=Canucks ink Canes to halt losing streak|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/story/2009/02/03/nhl-hurricanes-canucks.html|accessdate=2009-06-02|date=2009-02-03|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]]}}</ref>  Soon thereafter, in the midst of another season of personal bests for Burrows, the Canucks extended his contract with a four-year, $8 million deal on February 4, 2009,<ref>{{Citeweb|title=Canucks lock up Burrows ahead of deadline|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/story/2009/03/03/sp-canucks-burrows.html|accessdate=2009-02-04|date=2009-02-04|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]]}}</ref> quadrupling his $525,000 salary.<ref name=newdeal/>  On April 3, he was selected by the [[Professional Hockey Writers' Association]] as the Canucks' nominee for the [[Bill Masterton Memorial Trophy]], awarded for perseverance, dedication and sportsmanship.<ref>{{Citeweb|title=Burrows links Bill Masterton nod to late Luc Bourdon|url=http://www.theprovince.com/Sports/Burrows+links+Bill+Masterton+late+Bourdon/1458348/story.html|accessdate=2009-04-04|date=2009-04-03|publisher=''[[The Province]]''}}</ref>  Playing in a more offensive role on the first line for the latter part of the season, Burrows finished the [[2008<U+2013>09 NHL season|2008<U+2013>09 season]] with a career-high 28 goals, 23 assists and 51 points.  In the subsequent [[2009 Stanley Cup playoffs|2009 playoffs]], Burrows scored the [[game winning goal|game winning]] [[overtime (ice hockey)|overtime]] goal in game four to eliminate and sweep the [[St. Louis Blues (ice hockey)|St. Louis Blues]] in the first round.  It was his second goal of the game.<ref>{{Citeweb|title=Canucks defeat Blues in OT, advance to second round|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/stanleycup/W3vW6/story/2009/04/21/sp-hockey-canucks-blues-game4.html|accessdate=2009-04-21|date=2009-04-21|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]]}}</ref>  After being defeated by the [[Chicago Blackhawks]] in the second round, it was revealed that Burrows was suffering from a left wrist injury, requiring off-season surgery, as well as minor left thumb and [[hip flexor]] injuries.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Burrows wasn't at best vs. Chicago|url=http://www.faceoff.com/hockey/teams/vancouver-canucks/story.html?id=1594600&add_feed_url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.faceoff.com%2Fscripts%2FSP6Atom.aspx%3Fid%3D894638|accessdate=2009-06-06|publisher=''[[The Province]]''}}</ref>

[[File:Alexandre burrows.jpg|thumb|Burrows at the Canucks 2009 SkillsCompetition]]
The following season, Burrows recorded back-to-back hat tricks against the [[Columbus Blue Jackets]] on January 5, 2010, and the [[Phoenix Coyotes]] on January 7.  It marked the first time an NHL player notched consecutive three-goal games since [[Ilya Kovalchuk]] in November 2007 and the first time a Canucks player did so since [[Petri Skriko]] in 1986.<ref name=hattricks>{{citeweb|title=Burrows trying to keep hat tricks in perspective|url=http://canucks.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=512927|accessdate=2010-01-08|publisher=[[Vancouver Canucks]]|date=2010-01-08}}</ref> With six goals and an assist, Burrows was named the NHL First Star of the Week on January 11, 2010.<ref>{{Citeweb|title=Six-goal week earns Canucks' Burrows first star honours|url=http://tsn.ca/nhl/teams/story/?id=305689&hubname=nhl-canucks|accessdate=2010-01-13|date=2010-01-11|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}</ref> Later in the season, he left a game against the [[Los Angeles Kings]] after being hit in the throat by a [[Jarret Stoll]] slapshot.<ref>{{citenews|title=Canucks: Daniel Sedin and Alex Burrows to play tonight|url=http://www.vancouversun.com/Canucks+Daniel+Sedin+Alex+Burrows+play+tonight/2758049/story.html|accessdate=2010-04-02|date=2010-04-02|publisher=''[[Vancouver Sun]]''|author=Iain MacIntyre}}</ref>

====NHL officials controversy====
The night of his first star of the week selection, Burrows and the Canucks played a controversial game against the [[Nashville Predators]].  With the game tied 2<U+2013>2 in the third period, Burrows was penalized twice by referee [[St<U+00E9>phane Auger]] <U+2013> once for diving and the other for interference.<ref name=auger/>  The latter call was deemed questionable by media sources, including [[The Sports Network|TSN]] and the ''[[National Post]]''.<ref name=NP>{{Citation| last=Arthur| first=Bruce| title=Whither The Truth?| newspaper=National Post| date=14 January 2010| url=http://www.nationalpost.com/opinion/columnists/story.html?id=e38aa480-837e-4bdd-966c-2f32237ce534| accessdate=14 January 2010}}</ref> The interference penalty along with a tripping penalty committed by Henrik Sedin resulted in Nashville's game-winning, 5-on-3 powerplay goal late in the game.<ref name=auger/>  With three seconds to go in regulation, Burrows skated by Auger and protested the interference penalty, resulting in an unsportsmanlike minor and a ten-minute misconduct.<ref name=auger/>  Following the game, Burrows accused Auger of having a personal vendetta against him for a play against the Predators the previous month in December.  After Burrows had been hit into the boards by Nashville forward [[Jerred Smithson]], Auger assessed Smithson with a five-minute major and a match penalty that the league later rescinded because it was believed Burrows had dived.<ref name=fine>{{Citeweb|title=NHL officially fines Canucks' Burrows for outburst|url=http://tsn.ca/nhl/teams/story/?id=305967&hubname=nhl-canucks|accessdate=2010-01-14|date=2010-01-13|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}</ref>  Burrows claimed that Auger told him before the January 11 game: "you made me look bad so I'm going to get you back tonight."  He went on to tell reporters that Auger "should stay out for the rest of the year making calls like that ... We just blew two points because of his officiating tonight."<ref name=auger>{{citeweb|title=Burrows slams referee after loss to Predators|url=http://tsn.ca/nhl/teams/story/?id=305786&hubname=nhl-canucks|accessdate=2010-01-14|date=2010-01-11|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}</ref>

The following day, the NHL fined Burrows US$2,500 for publicly criticizing Auger and deemed that his claims "cannot be substantiated."<ref>{{citeweb|title=Auger didn't target Burrows: Campbell|url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/nhl-tries-hard-to-sweep-auger-affair-under-the-rug/article1430467/|accessdate=2010-01-15|date=2010-01-13|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}</ref>  Later that week, ''[[Hockey Night in Canada]]'' aired an 11-minute segment hosted by [[Ron MacLean]] and NHL vice-president [[Colin_Campbell_(ice_hockey)|Colin Campbell]] reviewing Burrows' past transgressions, spanning two years.  The segment was widely criticized for being biased against Burrows and failing to illustrate both sides of the argument.<ref>{{Citeweb|title=Ron MacLean not sorry for criticism of Canuck Alex Burrows|url=http://www.canada.com/sports/MacLean+sorry+criticism+Burrows/2456646/story.html|accessdate=2010-01-20|date=2010-01-19|publisher=''[[The Province]]''}}</ref> Burrows' parents subsequently issued a formal letter of complaint to the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]], accusing MacLean of "verbal assassination" and for displaying "no journalistic balance."<ref>{{citeweb|title=Burrows family files complaint over CBC segment|url=http://www.faceoff.com/story.html?id=bec94b18-b072-4156-9ad4-073e31717791|accessdate=2010-01-25|date=2010-01-18|publisher=''[[The Province]]''}}</ref>  The following Saturday after the segment aired, the Canucks refused any interviews with the CBC before, during or after their game against the Chicago Blackhawks, which was broadcasted on ''Hockey Night in Canada''.  The boycott was ordered by Canucks general manager [[Mike Gillis]].<ref>{{citeweb|title=Canucks boycott CBC|url=http://www.calgaryherald.com/sports/Canucks+boycott/2480810/story.html|accessdate=2010-01-25|date=2010-01-25|publisher=''[[Calgary Herald]]''}}</ref>

==Ball hockey career==
{{MedalTableTop}}
{{MedalCountry|{{CAN}}}}
{{MedalSport|[[Ball hockey]]}}
{{MedalCompetition|World Championships}}
{{MedalGold|2005 Canada|}}
{{MedalBottom}}
Before making it to the NHL, Burrows enjoyed a prolific [[ball hockey]] career, starting at the age of nineteen.<ref name=ballhockey/>  While he played [[ice hockey]] during the hockey season, Burrows competed in annual national and international ball hockey tournaments during the off-season.<ref>{{citeweb|last=Wiebe|first=Ken|title=Forward has a ball playing in the off-season|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Hockey/AHL/2005/05/02/1022264.html|publisher=Winnipeg Sun|accessdate=2008-03-17}}</ref>  In 2005, he won a world championship with Canada's national ball hockey team in [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=staking>{{Citeweb|title=Staking his claim|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Hockey/AHL/2005/09/28/1239040-sun.html|accessdate=2009-03-31|date=2005-09-28|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer|CANOE]]}}</ref><ref name=redlites/>  Later that summer, he led his [[Montreal]]-based team, the Red Lites, to a national championship, scoring 2 goals in a 5<U+2013>2 finals win against the Toronto Midnight Express.<ref name=redlites>{{Citeweb|title=Red Lite light it up at nationals|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/OtherSports/2005/08/21/1182365-sun.html|accessdate=2009-03-31|date=2005-08-21|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer|CANOE]]}}</ref>  He returned the following year to lead the Red Lites to a sixth consecutive title in 2006.<ref>{{citeweb|last=Yates|first=Dave|title=Ball hockey helps Burrows reach NHL|url=http://www.canada.com/montrealgazette/news/sports/story.html?id=90d2b982-5889-4592-b572-06019f4d00c9|publisher=Montreal Gazette|accessdate=2008-03-17}}</ref>  Voted in a 2006 poll as the country's greatest ball hockey player, Burrows has credited ball hockey for his fitness and discipline which has carried over to the NHL.<ref name=ballhockey>{{citeweb|title=Ball hockey helps Burrows reach NHL|url=http://www2.canada.com/montrealgazette/news/sports/story.html?id=90d2b982-5889-4592-b572-06019f4d00c9|accessdate=2009-03-31|date=2006-08-21|publisher=''[[Montreal Gazette]]''}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Burrows was born in [[Pointe-Claire, Quebec|Pointe-Claire]], [[Quebec]], to Rodney and Carole.  His father immigrated from [[London]], [[England]], at 23, while his mother, a Quebec native, is an [[elementary school]] [[principal (school)|principal]].  Burrows has two sisters, as well <U+2013> one older and one younger.<ref>{{Citeweb|title=Just me and my hockey mom|url=http://www2.canada.com/theprovince/news/sports/canucks/story.html?id=1366982|accessdate=2009-03 n|date=2009-03-10|publisher=''[[The Province]]''}}</ref><ref name=qanda/>  He grew up speaking mostly [[French language|French]] and attended French schools.<ref name=qanda>{{Citeweb|title=One-on-one with Alexandre Burrows|url=http://www2.canada.com/vancouversun/olympics/story.html?id=2d6d2915-27bb-4a2c-851c-33e2f17310f6&k=32561|accessdate=2009-03-31|date=2006-01-27|publisher=''[[Vancouver Sun]]''}}</ref>  He returns in the off-season to [[Montreal]].<ref name=newdeal>{{Citeweb|title=Burrows looking for a new deal|url=http://www2.canada.com/vancouversun/news/sports/story.html?id=8db3559d-7142-4b65-9dc5-7e857fc5c595|accessdate=2009-03-31|date=2008-10-10|publisher=''[[Vancouver Sun]]''}}</ref> Burrows' girlfriend is Nancy Roy.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Canucks were represented at funeral for Pyatt's fiancee|url=http://communities.canada.com/theprovince/blogs/whitetowel/archive/2009/04/14/canucks-were-represented-at-funeral-for-pyatt-s-fiancee.aspx|accessdate=2010-02-01|date=2009-04-14|publisher=''[[The Province]]''}}</ref>

In the 2009 off-season, Burrows was involved in an assault incident while playing in a summer ice hockey league. Police were called to an arena in [[Kirkland, Quebec|Kirkland]], [[Quebec]], on July 21 after Burrows allegedly struck a goaltender, 19-year-old Koray Celik, in the face.  No arrests, however, were made at the scene.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Canucks' Alex Burrows investigated for alleged summer hockey incident|url=http://www.vancouversun.com/sports/Canucks+Alex+Burrows+investigated+alleged+summer+hockey+incident+report/1855791/story.html|accessdate=2009-09-04|date=2009-08-03|publisher=''[[Vancouver Sun]]''}}</ref>

